  <content>
    <title>Partnership Strategy — Five-Stage Framework</title>

    <summary>A five-stage framework for creating mutually beneficial partnerships that extend reach beyond your own audience: identify partnership type (affiliate, co-marketing, integration, reseller, white-label), score candidates on reach/relevance/trust/effort/risk, structure the deal with clear mutual value, outreach with the partner's benefit in the first paragraph, and maintain with a 30-60-90 review cadence.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Organic and paid channels saturate; partnerships compound — the same co-marketing webinar can be repeated quarterly at near-zero marginal cost. One-sided proposals (80% of cold outreach) get binned; partnerships that start with a small concrete pilot ("single webinar in two weeks") succeed because they're low-commitment tests of fit before multi-quarter commitments.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Distribution-constrained: product is solid and you need to reach a defined audience that gathers around another product</item>
        <item>Building integrations that reduce churn (becoming a Slack/Notion add-on)</item>
        <item>Co-marketing webinars, bundles, or guides with a complementary tool sharing your ICP</item>
        <item>Reseller or white-label expansion without a dedicated sales team</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-PMF: partnerships add coordination overhead; spend that energy on direct customer interviews instead</item>
        <item>Unclear value-prop: partners cannot promote what they don't understand — fail the one-pager test first</item>
        <item>High-burn 3-month runway: partnerships compound over 6–18 months, not 90 days</item>
        <item>When churn is the real problem: partnerships add top-of-funnel but won't fix retention</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="partnership-types">
      <p>Taxonomy: Affiliate (partner promotes to their audience, you pay commission per sale), Co-marketing (shared audience access and content creation), Integration (technical connection benefiting both user bases), Reseller (partner sells and supports your product for a margin), White-label (partner distributes an unbranded version), Strategic (resource, credential, or market-access exchange).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>For solopreneurs pre-scale: prioritize affiliates and co-marketing partnerships first. They require no technical integration and produce measurable results within 30–90 days.</statement>
        <rationale>Integration and reseller partnerships require months of setup and have higher failure rates when one party lacks dedicated partnership headcount. Affiliates and co-marketing can be tested with a single piece of co-created content or a webinar.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="partner-discovery">
      <p>Discovery sources: complementary products (same audience, different solution — signals: your customers mention them), influencers and content creators (bloggers, podcasters, YouTubers in your niche), adjacent communities (Slack groups, Discord, forums where your ICP gathers), adjacent businesses (same customer segment, non-competing offer).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Validate audience overlap before outreach: quote a specific data point ("their footer claims 12K customers") rather than asserting overlap. Agents and founders both overstate overlap from surface signals.</statement>
        <rationale>Partnership proposals based on fabricated overlap are discovered immediately by the partner and destroy credibility before any relationship starts. Data-grounded claims signal research investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="partner-scorecard">
      <rule>
        <statement>Score every partner candidate on five factors (each 1–5): Reach, Relevance, Trust, Effort required (lower is better), Risk (lower is better). Total out of 25. Proceed only if score is 18 or above.</statement>
        <rationale>Partnerships below 18/25 consistently fail because one of the five dimensions is weak enough to doom execution: low reach means no ROI, low trust means poor conversion, high effort means neither side prioritizes it.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/partner-score.py">Scorecard calculator: ranks candidates 0–25, flags proceed/no</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="affiliate-structure">
      <p>Affiliate commission models: per sale 20–40% for digital products, per lead $5–50 for SaaS and services, recurring 10–20% monthly for subscriptions, tiered commission for high-volume partners. Set cookie duration (typically 30–90 days), payment on net-30 cycle, minimum payout threshold.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Instrument from day one: unique UTM per partner plus a dedicated landing page. Vague co-promotions without attribution infrastructure die in budget debates within the first quarter.</statement>
        <rationale>Without clear per-partner attribution, partners cannot see their results, you cannot rank partners by value, and neither party can justify continued investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="co-marketing-structure">
      <p>Co-marketing options: joint webinar (you provide content and presentation, partner provides audience and promotion), bundle (both products offered together with shared pricing), co-authored content (article or guide with cross-distribution), launch support (product launch in exchange for testimonial and promotion).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Propose a small-bet first (joint blog post, single webinar) before pitching a multi-quarter integration. A successful small pilot creates proof points and builds trust for larger commitments.</statement>
        <rationale>Partners have competing priorities. A low-commitment pilot can be approved by one person without legal and exec review. Large proposals stall in approval chains.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="outreach-and-messaging">
      <rule>
        <statement>Put the partner's benefit in the first sentence of every outreach email. Founders and BD contacts scan for "what's in it for me" and discard anything that leads with the sender's company.</statement>
        <rationale>Cold outreach open rates are 20–30%; the first sentence determines whether the email gets read past the preview. Partner-benefit-first framing immediately answers the question that determines read/discard.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Outreach opening: "I have a partnership idea that could generate 250 additional registrations for your next webinar, with zero additional prep from your team." Leads with partner outcome, specific and concrete. Compare to bad: "Hi, I'm the founder of [Company], we build [product]..." — leads with sender, partner must infer whether any benefit exists.</note>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/one-pager.md">Partnership proposal one-pager template</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="maintenance-and-cadence">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a 30-60-90 review cadence for every active partnership. Partnerships decay in silence; explicit review prevents quiet disengagement from going unnoticed for a quarter.</statement>
        <rationale>Partnership champions change jobs; priorities shift. A cadenced review surfaces these changes while the relationship is still recoverable. Silent partnerships are vanity — they appear on a logo wall but generate no pipeline.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Cadence: weekly check on performance metrics, monthly partner update email, quarterly review and planning call, annual renewal discussion.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never auto-send partnership outreach via agent. Partner-network relationships are repeated-game interactions — one poorly-worded email from a batch run can burn goodwill across an entire industry vertical.</statement>
        <rationale>Unlike B2C marketing where individual-recipient mistakes are isolated, BD contacts share bad experiences with peers. A single batch-outreach incident can preclude relationships with all connected partners.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/tracker.md">Partnership pipeline tracker: active, in-discussion, target-list tables</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="examples">
      <example type="good">
        <note>SaaS affiliate partnership: productivity blogger with 50K subscribers, 30% recurring commission, exclusive 20% discount code, co-created review content. Provided free account for testing + custom landing page + assets + monthly performance emails. Results: 25 signups in first month, $750 in recurring commissions, featured in year-end tool roundup.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Co-marketing webinar: complementary SaaS tool with overlapping ICP. Joint webinar "How to [combined value]", cross-promoted to both email lists, Zoom hosted jointly. Results: 500 registrations (250 each), 40% attendance rate, 30 new customers combined. Repeated quarterly — the key: repeating a successful format compounds without proportional effort.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>"Strategic" partnership: two logos appear on each other's websites, no joint plan, no named DRI on either side. No pipeline generated after 6 months. Classic vanity partnership — appeared valuable on paper, never executed because neither party owned it.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Models confidently invent partnership-team contact names and email addresses.</description>
        <reason>Always validate contacts via LinkedIn or company About page before any outreach. Never send to an email the agent generated without verification — sending to fabricated addresses creates CAN-SPAM and spam-filter issues.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cold-outreach output drifts toward spammy templates with superlatives despite constraints.</description>
        <reason>Add hard constraints: "must reference [X]-specific recent action", "no superlatives", "under 150 words". Review every outreach before send regardless of constraint specification.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent asserts audience overlap without citing the source data point.</description>
        <reason>Require the agent to quote a specific number and source ("their pricing page says 8,000 customers"). Asserted overlap with no data source will be challenged by the partner immediately.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent auto-generates revenue-share math without showing the formula step by step.</description>
        <reason>LLMs flub multi-step financial calculations. Require explicit formula output ("30% of $99 MRR = $29.70/month x 12 = $356.40/year per referral") before any proposal is drafted.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent drafts contract terms or legal summaries without human review.</description>
        <reason>Partnership agreements that include integration rights, IP licensing, or data-sharing require legal review — especially if enterprise deals will reference the agreement for DPA/SCC compliance.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Lead with the partner's win in the first paragraph; founders and BD leads scan for "what's in it for me" and bin the rest.</item>
        <item>Always propose a small-bet first (joint blog, single webinar) before pitching a multi-quarter integration.</item>
        <item>Instrument from day 1: unique UTM per partner + dedicated landing page; vague co-promo dies in attribution debates.</item>
        <item>Keep a 30-60-90 review cadence; partnerships rot in silence, not from explicit failure.</item>
        <item>Document partner roles inside your PRM; verbal agreements with no DRI evaporate when champions leave.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/one-pager.md" purpose="Partnership proposal: about us, opportunity, partner value, ask, next steps"/>
      <template path="templates/affiliate-agreement.md" purpose="Affiliate partnership terms: commission, cookie, responsibilities, duration"/>
      <template path="templates/tracker.md" purpose="Partnership pipeline tracker: active, in-discussion, and target-list tables"/>
      <template path="templates/partner-score.py" purpose="Scorecard calculator: ranks candidates 0–25, flags proceed/no"/>
    </templates>

